                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list>
                    <item n="1"><p>As <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAN1997"><bibl><author>Manning and Moore</author>  
                        (<date when="1997">1997</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >372</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> suggest regarding GELAGNI, <q>if a long é was intended (Gellagni) would be cognate with 
                                Old Irish <hi rend="italic">Gíallán</hi>, related to <hi rend="italic">gíall</hi> `a hostage'. 
                                If a short e was intended (Gelagni), it would be congante with Old Irish *<hi rend="italic">Gelán</hi>, related to <hi rend="italic">gel</hi> 'bright'</q>.
                        The former is actually attested as a personal name in the Félire Óengusso (<ref target="http://www.dil.ie/25799">eDIL s.v. gíallán</ref>).</p>                   
                    </item></list>

            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Built into the external face of the north wall of the nave, immediately east of the north doorway of the ruined church 
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAN1997">(<bibl><author>Manning and Moore</author> 
                                <date when="1997">1997</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >371</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> in the townland of Churchclara and barony
                            of Gowran. The location
                            of this stone may be accessed via the <ref target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/
                                HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KK020-017010-">National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on www.archaeology.ie</ref>.   
                            (Publicly accessible. GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-7.146098, 52.655485</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">On site in the position in which it was discovered.</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head> History of Recording</head>
                <p>Discovered by Con Manning in the late 1970s 
                    <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAN1997">(<bibl><author>Manning and Moore</author> 
                        <date when="1997">1997</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >371</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. In 2017 both stones were recorded in 3d using photogrammetry and in June 2020 digitised here as an action 
                    of the County Kilkenny Heritage Plan Programme, funded by the Heritage Office of Kilkenny County Council and the Heritage Council.</p>
            </div>
